\parai{Efficiency} refers to the low consumption of resources (time, memory, energy, etc.) for addressing a particular request. SEs and KGs index their content, allowing for efficient retrieval. In the case of KGs, more complex queries -- such as path queries, queries with many joins, etc. -- may require more resources to evaluate. Nevertheless, with a good query optimizer and a query of moderate complexity, the execution time is usually in the order of seconds (or less).
 LLMs process user inputs not by retrieval, but by inference, making even simple requests (e.g., ``What is the capital of Venezuela?'')
 relatively costly to process in terms of time, energy and computational resources [DBLP:conf/hpec/SamsiZMLMJBKTG23].
 Moreover, the inference utilizes a large GPU platform with massive parallelism, whereas most KG queries are handled on a single CPU core. Comparable user requests are thus orders of magnitude more expensive to address with a contemporary LLM in terms of computational and environmental costs.